We will solve for the area of the shaded region by first finding the area of the square and then subtracting the combined area of the four quarter circles.

The area of the square is $(6\text{ cm})^2=36$ square centimeters.

Each quarter circle has radius $2\sqrt{3}$ centimeters, so each quarter circle has area \[\frac{1}{4}\cdot \pi\cdot (2\sqrt{3}\text{ cm})^2=6\pi\] square centimeters.  Therefore, the combined area of all four quarter circles is $4\cdot 6\pi = 24\pi$ square centimeters.

The area of the shaded region is the area of the square minus the combined area of the quarter circles, so it is $36 - 24\pi$ square centimeters.  Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{36 - 24\pi}.$

